AC20-0015759 - 10/10/2020
M. HURWITZ #20029

On 10/04/2020, at approximately 2224 hrs, I responded to a reported single-vehicle traffic collision on S Himalaya St and E Chenango Ave. A refused RP stated that a vehicle had crashed "at the S curve" on Himalaya St, just south of Chenango. This RP said a person, unknown if male or female, had gotten out of the vehicle's driver seat and began to walk northbound on S Himalaya St. Deputy Gryniewicz, and I arrived 2230 hrs.

Deputy Gryniewicz began to try to find the driver who had fled the accident scene. I immediately went to the vehicle and found it to be unoccupied. It was a gray Chevrolet Traverse CO/1837070 - Temp. The car was facing south in northbound lanes. The car was in both the number one and number two lanes. There was damage to a retaining wall located on the east side of S Himalaya St. The vehicle was leaning partially against the retaining wall. There were no keys in the ignition, and the vehicle was locked. I noticed moderate damage to the left front fender and bumper. There was also minor damage to the hood of the vehicle. There was no airbag deployment in the car. As I walked around the vehicle, I saw that the rear tires were pointed in towards each other.

Deputy Gryniewicz, as well as several other deputies, returned to the crash scene, after not being able to find the driver of the vehicle. 1st Class Towing was advised and responded to the scene. After 1st Class Towing arrived, an individual walked up to our patrol cars. The person, identified by there Colorado Drivers License as JASSIR, SALVADOR - 07/14/1989, stated he was driving the vehicle north on S Himalaya St when he "lost control" and slammed into the wall. Salvador could not give me any clear description of what "losing control" meant. I asked Salvador if he had been drinking, to which he replied no. I asked Salvador if he would be willing to participate in voluntary Standard Field Sobriety Maneuvers. He did. Salvador completed all maneuvers appropriately, and there were no signs of alcohol intoxication on his person. I issued Salvador a citation for Careless Driving and Fleeing the Scene of a Crash. 

Nothing further.

V1 was in the number one lane and swung out into the center bi-directional turn lane and started to make the right turn. V1 did not see V2 that was in the number two lane. The front corner of V1 hit V2 causing it to leave the roadway, hit medium size decorative landscaping rocks and roll onto it's top in the roadway. V3 was struck by some of the rocks.

TU2 WAS W/B STOPPED IN PARKING LOT DRIVEWAY AT RED LIGHT., WAITING TO TURN LEFT.  TU1 WAS N/B YOSEMITE LANE #2.  TU2 RECEIVED GREEN BALL TRAFFIC  AND STARTED TO TURN LEFT.  TU1 FAILED TO STOP AT RED LIGHT AND COLLIDED WITH SIDE OF TU2, CAUSING DAMAGE.  RESCUE ARRIVED ON SCENE AND MEDICALLY CLEARED ALL PARTIES AT SCENE, LEAVING THEM THERE.  INDEPENDANT WITNESS WAS BEHIND TU2 AT RED BALL TRAFFIC LIGHT, ALSO WAITING TO TURN LEFT AND SAW THE TRAFFIC LIGHT TURN GREEN BALL AND TU2 START FORWARD INTO INTERSECTION, WHERE TU1 STRUCK TU2.   TU1 BOUGHT CAR ON JULY 27 2020 AND FAILED TO REGISTER THE CAR.  DRIVER OF TU1 ALSO FAILED TO PROVIDE CURRENT PROOF OF INSURANCE UPON REQUEST AND WAS GIVEN MULITPLE OPPORTUNITIES TO GET PHOTOGRAPH COPY FROM HER MOTHER. I OBESERVED THE TRAFFIC LIGHTS WHILE I WAS ON SCENE AND THE TRAFFIC LIGHTS WERE FUNCTIONING CORRECTLY.

column8: S Jordan Rd / E Hinsdale Dr
column99:
TU2 was traveling north on S. Jordan Rd. approaching the intersection of E. Hinsdale Dr. in the number 1 lane. TU1 was traveling south on S. Jordan Rd. and, as it entered the intersection at E. Hinsdale Dr., TU1 cross over the median separating the north and south bound lanes of S. Jordan Rd. TU1 struck the keep right traffic sign on the south side of the intersection and proceeded into opposing traffic traveling north on S. Jordan Rd. The sign struck TU2 causing damage to the driver's side door and front right fender. TU1 crossed the median again and traveled south on S. Jordan Rd.

TU2 made a U-turn at E. Hinsdale Dr. and drove south on S. Jordan Rd. in attempt to locate TU1. TU2 was unsuccessful in locating TU1 and TU2 returned to the intersection of S. Jordan Rd. and E. Hinsdale Dr. When deputies arrived on scene they attempted to locate TU1, but they were unsuccesful.

column9: I25 NB DRY CREEK OFF RAMP/DRY CREEK I25 NB ON RAMP
column99:
CORTEZ was driving NB in the #3 lane of I25 just south of the E. Dry Creek Rd. exit. CORTEZ struck the rear of CASABIANCA's vehicle, which was also in the NB #3 lane, with the front of his vehicle. When CORTEZ was asked what had happened he stated that he fell asleep at the wheel and did not wake up until he hit CASABIANCA. CORTEZ also stated that he believed he was in the #2 lane when the accident occurred. The impact with the front of CORTEZ's vehicle into the rear of CASABIANCA's vehicle corroborated CORTEZ's statement. CORTEZ was issued a summons (ACCIT0002877) for careless driving causing bodily injury.

CASABIANCA was transported to Sky Ridge Hospital for complaint of neck pain by SMFR prior to my arrival and Deputy Mackay responded to the hospital to get CASABIANCA to fill out a driver statement and check for SBI. The attending physician stated there was no SBI. Both driver's statements were uploaded to the case and photographs were added to the digital crime scene program.

V2 was traveling n/b in the #3 lane near 7530 S. University Blvd. V1 was in the #2 lane of n/b university driving beside v2. There is an entrance into a gas station at 7530 S. University Blvd. V1 suddenly made a right turn and struck V2 causing a side to side collision. Based on the statements of both involved drivers V1 was intending to turn into the gas station. V1 had extensive damage on his passenger side on both the front and rear doors and most of the damage on V2 was on the front driver side fender with a little on the front corner. The driver of V1 claims that he was in the #3 lane and somehow V2 came up from directly behind him and as he was turning into the parking lot this V2 somehow hit him. The driver of V2 claims that V1 was in the #2 lane and V2 was in the #3 lane and suddenly V1 veered in front of V2 to turn into the gas station. Based on the damage to both vehicles and the area where the accident occurred the only way that the damage could have occurred would be that V1 was in the #2 lane because there is no other way there could have been a side to side impact. The point of impact appeared to be directly in front of 7530 S. University Blvd and both drivers agreed that the crash happened there. The only other way that this damage could have occurred would be if V2 was in the #3 lane and he merged left and struck V1 in the #2 lane. However, the driver of V1 maintained his story of being in the #3 lane and the Driver of V2 never said he attempted to merge left so I have no evidence that this is the case.

The point of impact appeared to be directly in front of 7530 S. University Blvd and both drivers agreed that the crash happened there. The only other way that this damage could have occurred would be if V2 was in the #3 lane and he merged left and struck V1 in the #2 lane. However, the driver of V1 maintained his story of being in the #3 lane and the Driver of V2 never said he attempted to merge left so I have no evidence that this is the case.

V2 was traveling n/b in the #3 lane near 7530 S. University Blvd. V1 was in the #2 lane of n/b university driving beside v2. There is an entrance into a gas station at 7530 S. University Blvd. V1 suddenly made a right turn and struck V2 causing a side to side collision. Based on the statements of both involved drivers V1 was intending to turn into the gas station. V1 had extensive damage on his passenger side on both the front and rear doors and most of the damage on V2 was on the front driver side fender with a little on the front corner. The driver of V1 claims that he was in the #3 lane and somehow V2 came up from directly behind him and as he was turning into the parking lot this V2 somehow hit him. The driver of V2 claims that V1 was in the #2 lane and V2 was in the #3 lane and suddenly V1 veered in front of V2 to turn into the gas station. Based on the damage to both vehicles and the area where the accident occurred the only way that the damage could have occurred would be that V1 was in the #2 lane because there is no other way there could have been a side to side impact. The point of impact appeared to be directly in front of 7530 S. University Blvd and both drivers agreed that the crash happened there. The only other way that this damage could have occurred would be if V2 was in the #3 lane and he merged left and struck V1 in the #2 lane. However, the driver of V1 maintained his story of being in the #3 lane and the Driver of V2 never said he attempted to merge left so I have no evidence that this is the case.

Veh 2 was heading eastbound in the number 3 lane of EB Arapahoe just West of Waco St and began to accelerate when the light turned green. Veh 1 then Collided into the rear of Veh 2 causing damage. Veh 2 had moderate damage to the rear bumper and exhaust fascia. Veh 1 has severe damage to the front end to include the grille and hood and was also leaking fluid, Veh 1 was towed due to damage 

Veh 1 stated that Veh 2 stopped suddenly and was not able to stop fast enough. 

Veh 2 stated that Veh 1 hit the rear end when she began to accelerate through the intersection.

Veh 1 and 2 filled out statements and they will be submitted into records. 

A witness filled out a statement and that will also be submitted into records. 

Deputy Walton took pictures of the crash and I will submit those into digital crime scene.

Traffic Unit #1 was westbound on E. Broncos Pkwy. .2 miles west of S. Cherokee Trail in the left lane.  Traffic Unit #1 spun out of control counter-clockwise, ran off the left side of the roadway and collided its left front with the bridge railing.  Traffic Unit #1 rotated clockwise striking the bridge rail with the left rear corner and continued back across the roadway and collided its front end with the bridge railing off the right side of the roadway.  Traffic Unit #1 came to rest facing north blocking the entire roadway.  The bridge railing sustained no damage.  No citation was issued to due to extremely poor icy road conditions.

column9: I25 NB COUNTY LINE RD/COUNTY LINE I25 NB
column99: REGINA was travelling NB on I25 just north of E. County Line Rd. in the #2 lane. REGINA stated that she was going approximately 40 MPH when she slid on ice, striking the median with the front of the vehicle. REGINA said that the vehicle continued to slide and then ended up striking the concrete barrier on the opposite side of the NB lanes. While at the scene I observed multiple vehicles loose control, spinning out in the same area REGINA did. CDOT was not performing deicing operations, the temperature was 23 degrees and it was still raining. I did not issue REGINA with a summons due the prior mentioned conditions.

column9: County Line Eb I25 Nb On Ramp
column99: JOY was entering onto NB I25 from E. County Line Rd. As JOY entered the straight portion of the on ramp, the vehicle began swerving and as JOY attempted to regain control, she struck the metal rail that separated the ramp form the highway. Both airbags deployed but JOY showed no signs of impact to her face or body. This crash occurred approximately 30 feet from a crash that happened 3 hours prior. CDOT had still not done any deicing operations and the road was extremely icy from the continuous rain. Because of these adverse conditions JOY was not issues a summons. There was damage prior to the crash that was photographed before knowing it was old. JOY stated that the only damage that came from the crash was on the front right side of the vehicle.

Vehicle 1 was traveling Westbound in the number 2 lane of the 17600 block of E. Arapahoe Rd.  A bicyclist was traveling Westbound in the number 3 lane at the same location, in front of Vehicle 1.  Vehicle 1 moved into the number 3 lane, then attempted to avoid the bicyclist by starting to move back to the number 2 lane.  The passenger side view mirror of vehicle 1 collided with the bicycle.  Vehicle 1 did not stop to check on the bicyclist and continued Westbound.

Bicyclist Joshua Dagastino stated he was riding as close as possible to the ride hand curb of the number 3 lane when the vehicle struck his bicycle.  This caused Joshua to fall to the ground.  Joshua had a small laceration on his left hand, which was bleeding.  He described the run vehicle as an early 2000s model small gray sedan.  Joshua was evaluated by South Metro Fire Rescue personnel and given a band aide for his hand.  The SMFR run number was 20-SM-033993.  Joshua stated he had no other injuries.  

Witness Michael George stated he was driving Westbound in the number 3 lane of E. Arapahoe Rd in front of the run vehicle.  Jacob George was in the front passenger seat.  Michael observed the rear reflectors on the pedals and on the seat of Joshua's bicycle.  Michael moved to the number 2 lane to pass Joshua at a safe distance.  Jacob and Michael recorded the license plate of the run vehicle as KDL587, and they described it as a silver Infiniti sedan.  That license plate was not registered to a vehicle in the State of Colorado.  The license plate KOL587 matched the vehicle which Jacob and Michael described as the run vehicle.  

The Infiniti pulled into the South side of the AMC movie theater parking lot at 6696 S. Parker Rd.  By the time Michael and Jacob caught up to the vehicle in the parking lot, they observed a male standing outside of the Infiniti and looking at the vehicle.  No one else was standing outside the vehicle and there did not appear to be any additional occupants in the vehicle.  The passenger side view mirror of the Infiniti was damaged.  Jacob described the male standing outside the Infiniti as white, between 5 ft, 10 inches to 6 ft tall, with short brown hair.  He was wearing a beige jacket and blue jeans.  

Another witness, Natia Crosley, stated she was traveling Westbound behind the run vehicle on Arapahoe Rd.  She described the run vehicle as a gray Infiniti sedan with Colorado license KOL587.  The Infiniti was in the number 2 lane, moved to the number 3 lane, then started to move back to the number 2 lane to avoid Joshua.  However, the vehicle collided with Joshua's bicycle and Natia saw Joshua fall down to the ground.  The Infiniti brake lights became activated after the collision and it drove into the AMC movie theater parking lot.  Natia continued Westbound and did not see the driver of the Infiniti.

Deputies checked the movie theater parking lot but the Infiniti was no longer on scene.

The Infiniti pulled into the South side of the AMC movie theater parking lot at 6696 S. Parker Rd.  By the time Michael and Jacob caught up to the vehicle in the parking lot, they observed a male standing outside of the Infiniti and looking at the vehicle.  No one else was standing outside the vehicle and there did not appear to be any additional occupants in the vehicle.  The passenger side view mirror of the Infiniti was damaged.  Jacob described the male standing outside the Infiniti as white, between 5 ft, 10 inches to 6 ft tall, with short brown hair.  He was wearing a beige jacket and blue jeans.  

Another witness, Natia Crosley, stated she was traveling Westbound behind the run vehicle on Arapahoe Rd.  She described the run vehicle as a gray Infiniti sedan with Colorado license KOL587.  The Infiniti was in the number 2 lane, moved to the number 3 lane, then started to move back to the number 2 lane to avoid Joshua.  However, the vehicle collided with Joshua's bicycle and Natia saw Joshua fall down to the ground.  The Infiniti brake lights became activated after the collision and it drove into the AMC movie theater parking lot.  Natia continued Westbound and did not see the driver of the Infiniti.

Deputies checked the movie theater parking lot but the Infiniti was no longer on scene.

Traffic Unit #1 (Unknown Hit and Run) was northbound on S. Riviera Way stopped at E. Powers Ave.  Traffic Unit #1 accelerated rapidly leaving 123 feet of acceleration tire marks before losing traction and beginning to rotate clockwise.  Traffic Unit #1 left 93 feet of clockwise rotational scuff marks before running off the right side of the roadway.  Traffic Unit #1 continued off the right side for 14.5 feet across grass and the sidewalk before colliding with a fence.  Traffic Unit #1 continued through the fence and collided with a second fence.  The two fences and the surrounding landscaping sustained heavy damage.  Traffic Unit #1 backed out and fled the scene northbound on S. Riviera Way.  No information was obtained except a white pickup truck.  This occurred on the Unincorporated Arapahoe County half of the roadway on the border with City of Centennial.  CSP was accident alert and not responding, but a report was completed after approval from CSP.  The third property owner related to one of the damaged fences was Madhoosudan Patil at 22054 E. Berry Pl. Aurora, CO 80015, Phone 720-975-4360.
